Last season he was suspended for eight matches for racially abusing Manchester United’s Patrice Evra.

'He’s a fantastic player, top scorer and everything we’d want in a striker, so there’s no change there. This is more about getting him back on the right track'

Liverpool managing director Ian Ayre

Former Liverpool captain Graeme Souness said the latest incident made it ‘very difficult’ for Suarez to stay at the club.

Immediately after the match, the club’s manager Brendan Rodgers insisted that any player was replaceable, ‘no matter how good they think they are’.

But yesterday Liverpool, who were criticised for defending Suarez over the racial abuse incident, again stood by their star player.

The club’s managing director Ian Ayre said: ‘Luis is a very important player to the club. As we keep saying, he signed a new four-year contract last summer and we’d all love to see him here throughout that contract.

